#Lag plot
plot(data$age,Lag(data$age, k=1),xlab="Y[i-1]",ylab="Y[i]", main="Lag Plot of Age k=1")
#hitorgram
hist(data$age, xlab="Y", main="Distribution of Age")

(a)(b)age Age data is normally distributed, judging by qqnorm and histogram; although the trend of qqnorm is not fully linear and the histogram is not absolute normal distribution.

confidence_interval = function(vec, prop = 0.95){
# given feature vec, return confidence interval (default 95%) 
CI=list()

p = 1 - (1 - prop) / 2 
n = length(vec)
avg = mean(vec)
stdev = sd(vec)
error = qnorm(p)*stdev/sqrt(n)
  # CI$data = vec
CI$mean = avg 
CI$stdev = stdev 
CI$lower = avg-error 
CI$upper = avg+error 
return(CI)
}
# Age's 95% confidence interval
confidence_interval(data$age)
## $mean
## [1] 36.83333
## 
## $stdev
## [1] 11.72657
## 
## $lower
## [1] 35.83873
## 
## $upper
## [1] 37.82793
# Experence's 95% confidence interval
confidence_interval(data$experience)
## $mean
## [1] 17.8221
## 
## $stdev
## [1] 12.37971
## 
## $lower
## [1] 16.7721
## 
## $upper
## [1] 18.87209

As the confidence interval, 1)Age has a 95% confidence interval for population mean (lower = 35.83873, upper = 37.82793). The parameter for its normal distribution could be mean = 36.83333, stdev = 11.72657. 2)Experience has a 95% confidence interval for population mean (lower = 16.7721, upper = 18.87209). The parameter for its normal distribution could be mean = 17.8221, stdev = 12.37971.

#histogram sex
par(mfrow = c(1, 2),
oma = c(0, 0, 2, 0),
mar = c(5.1, 4.1, 2.1, 2.1))

female <- subset(data,sex=='1')
hist(female$wage, xlab="Wage", main="Distribution of Female")

male <- subset(data,sex=='0')
hist(male$wage, xlab="Wage", main="Distribution of Male")

t.test(female$wage,male$wage)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  female$wage and male$wage
## t = -4.8853, df = 530.55, p-value = 1.369e-06
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -2.966949 -1.265164
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  7.878857  9.994913

(d)histogram and t-test The histgrams of male wage and female wage shows that the hostogram is significantly diiferent, male turns out to be more nirmally distributed. Based on the p-value, we are rejecting the null hypothesis, meaning that the distributions of male and female are different.

library(stats)
library(quantmod)
#NFD
y <- scan("NFD.txt")
head(y)
## [1] -1.276 -1.218 -0.453 -0.350  0.723  0.676
summary(y)
##      Min.   1st Qu.    Median      Mean   3rd Qu.      Max. 
## -2.647000 -0.720500 -0.093000 -0.002936  0.644750  3.436000
t = 1:length(y)

par(mfrow = c(2, 2),
oma = c(0, 0, 2, 0),
mar = c(5.1, 4.1, 2.1, 2.1))

plot(t,y,ylab="Y",xlab="Run Sequence",type="l", main="Data Run Sequence")
plot(y,Lag(y, k=1),xlab="Y[i-1]",ylab="Y[i]", main="Lag Plot k=1")
hist(y, xlab="Y", main="Distribution of Data")
qqnorm(y,main="Normality Test QQnorm")
qqline(y)

The NFD.txt file appears to be highly nomally distributed by observing the histogram and the qqnorm graph which stands out very linear distribution.
